04590nam a22006615i 9780292794825DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212007txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927948257 a10.7560/7164832doi  a(DE-B1597)588732  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aPQ7633b.D53 2007 7aLIT0040502bisacsh04a860.9/9287/0982222  aIQ 711272rvk0(DE-625)rvk/65775:1 aDíaz, Gwendolyn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWomen and Power in Argentine Literature :bStories, Interviews, and Critical Essays /cGwendolyn Díaz. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2007  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Elvira Orphée -- t2. Angélica Gorodischer -- t3. Marcela Solá -- t4. Luisa Valenzuela -- t5. Tununa Mercado -- t6. Alicia Dujovne Ortiz -- t7. Liliana Heer -- t8. Liliana Heker -- t9. Alina Diaconú -- t10. María Kodama -- t11. Cristina Siscar -- t12. Ana María Shua -- t13. Alicia Kozameh -- t14. Esther Cross -- t15. Ana Quiroga0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe astonishing talent of Argentine women writers belies the struggles they have faced—not merely as overlooked authors, but as women of conviction facing oppression. The patriarchal pressures of the Perón years, the terror of the Dirty War, and, more recently, the economic collapse that gripped the nation in 2001 created such repressive conditions that some writers, such as Luisa Valenzuela, left the country for long periods. Not surprisingly, power has become an inescapable theme in Argentine women's fiction, and this collection shows how the dynamics of power capture not only the political world but also the personal one. Whether their characters are politicians and peasants, torturers and victims, parents and children, or lovers male and female, each writer explores the effects of power as it is exercised by or against women. The fifteen writers chosen for Women and Power in Argentine Literature include famous names such as Valenzuela, as well as authors anthologized for the first time, most notably María Kodama, widow of Jorge Luis Borges. Each chapter begins with a "verbal portrait," editor Gwendolyn Díaz's personal impression of the author at ease, formed through hours of conversation and interviews. A biographical essay and critical commentary follow, with emphasis on the work included in this anthology. Díaz's interviews, translated from Spanish, and finally the stories themselves—only three of which have been previously published in English—complete the chapters. The extraordinary depth of these chapters reflects the nuanced, often controversial portrayals of power observed by Argentine women writers. Inspiring as well as insightful, Women and Power in Argentine Literature is ultimately about women who, in Díaz's words, "choose to speak their truth regardless of the consequences."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aArgentine literaturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aArgentine literaturexWomen authors. 0aAuthors, Argentiney20th centuryvInterviews. 0aWomen and literaturezArgentina. 0aWomen authors, Argentiney20th centuryvInterviews. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / Hispanic American.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292794825423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292794825/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK